# Simulation example {#sec-ex3}




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
#Load packages
library(ggdag)
library(dagitty)
library(rstanarm)
library(tidybayes)
library(ggdist)
library(tidyverse)
library(gt)
library(rstan)
```
:::




## Data-generating process

The data-generating process is described via the directed acyclic graph (DAG) in @fig-DAG.ex3-1. In this DAG, window $(\text{W})$ influences perceived warmth $(\text{P})$ both directly and indirectly, passing through daylight $(\text{D})$. Additionally, window $(\text{W})$ also influences indirectly visual comfort $(\text{V})$ through daylight $(\text{D})$.




::: {.cell .fig-cap-location-bottom layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="true"}
dag_coords.ex3 <-
  data.frame(name = c('W', 'D', 'V', 'P'),
             x = c(1, 3.5, 6, 6),
             y = c(3, 2, 1, 3))

DAG.ex3 <-
  dagify(D ~ W,
         P ~ W + D,
         V ~ D,
         coords = dag_coords.ex3)

ggplot(data = DAG.ex3, aes(x = x, y = y, xend = xend, yend = yend)) +
  geom_dag_text(colour = 'black', size = 10, parse = TRUE,
                family = c('mono'),
                label = c(expression(bold(D)), expression(bold(P)), expression(bold(V)), expression(bold(W)))) +
  geom_dag_edges(arrow_directed = grid::arrow(length = grid::unit(10, 'pt'), type = 'open'),
                 edge_colour = 'black',
                 family = c('mono'), 
                 fontface = c('bold')) + 
  annotate('text', x = 1, y = 3.3, label = 'window shading', 
           size = 4, hjust = 0.5, colour = 'grey50') +
  annotate('text', x = 3.5, y = 1.7, label = 'daylight', 
           size = 4, hjust = 0.6, colour = 'grey50') +
  annotate('text', x = 6, y = 3.3, label = 'perceived warmth', 
           size = 4, hjust = 0.6, colour = 'grey50') +
  annotate('text', x = 6, y = 0.7, label = 'visual comfort', 
           size = 4, hjust = 0.6, colour = 'grey50') +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0.5, 6.5), ylim = c(0.8, 3.2))  +
  theme_dag()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Graphical representation via DAG of the data-generating process.](ex3_simulation_files/figure-html/fig-DAG.ex3-1-1.png){#fig-DAG.ex3-1 fig-align='center' width=60%}
:::
:::




The DAG in @fig-DAG.ex3-1 can be written as:

-   $D \sim f_{D}(W)$, read as 'daylight $(\text{D})$ is some function of window $(\text{W})$'.
-   $P \sim f_{P}(W, D)$, read as 'perceived warmth $(\text{P})$ is some function of window $(\text{W})$ and daylight $(\text{D})$'.
-   $V \sim f_{V}(D)$, read as 'visual comfort $(\text{V})$ is some function of daylight $(\text{D})$'.

## Synthetic data set

To generate synthetic data, we defined the custom function `data.sim_ex3()`. This function takes as inputs the sample size `n` and generates synthetic data according to the DAG in @fig-DAG.ex3-1.




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
data.sim_ex3 <- function(n) {
  b_win.day = 1.5 #direct causal effect of W on D
  b_win.per = -0.7 #direct causal effect of W on P
  b_day.per = 0.8 #direct causal effect of D on P
  b_win = b_win.per + (b_win.day * b_day.per) #total causal effect of W on P
  #Simulate window 
  W <- rnorm(n = n, mean = 0, sd = 1) 
  #Simulate daylight
  D <- rnorm(n = n, mean = b_win.day * W, sd = 0.5)
  #Simulate visual comfort 
  V <- rnorm(n = n, mean = 1 * D, sd = 0.2)
  #Simulate perceived warmth 
  P <- rnorm(n = n, mean = b_win.per * W  + b_day.per * D, sd = 0.5)
  #Return tibble with simulated values
  return(tibble(W, D, P, V))
  }
```
:::




From this data generation mechanism, we simulated the target population, which consists of one million observations.




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
set.seed(2025) #set random number for reproducibility
#Simulate the population
ex3_population <- data.sim_ex3(n = 1e6)
#View the data frame
ex3_population
```

