```


:::
:::




The resulting p-value is 0.254, which indicates that we fail to reject the null hypothesis (i.e., `W = 0.5`) at the 0.05 level. This result suggests that the regression coefficient for window (i.e., 0.510) is not statistically significantly different from 0.5. Since the estimated causal effect from `Model.1` is unbiased, we would correctly conclude that that an increase of unit in window opening causes an increase in perceived warmth by 0.510 units (95% CI \[0.493, 0.528\]).

For `Model.2` we found a negative coefficient between window $(\text{W})$ and perceived warmth $(\text{P})$ equal to -0.698 with 95% CI \[-0.743, -0.653\]. Since the 95% CI excludes zero, the regression coefficient is statistically significantly different from zero at the 0.05 level (p-value = 2.43e-186). Additionally, since the 95% CI does not include the data-generating parameter for window opening (i.e., `b_win = 0.5`), we can deduce that the estimated coefficient for window opening is statistically significantly different from 0.5 at the 0.05 level. We can test this more formally by using the `linearHypothesis()` function. Specifically,




::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
