The resulting p-value is 0, which indicates that we can reject the null hypothesis (i.e., `W = 0.5`) at the 0.05 level. This result suggests that the regression coefficient for window (i.e., -0.698) is statistically significantly different from 0.5. Since the estimated causal effect from `Model.2` is biased, we would erroneously conclude that an increase of unit in window opening causes a decrease in perceived warmth by -0.698 units (95% CI \[-0.743, -0.653\]).

For `Model.3` we found a negative coefficient between window $(\text{W})$ and perceived warmth $(\text{P})$ equal to -0.522 with 95% CI \[-0.566, -0.478\]. Since the 95% CI excludes zero, the regression coefficient is statistically significantly different from zero at the 0.05 level (p-value = 1.39e-114). Additionally, since the 95% CI does not include the data-generating parameter for window opening (i.e., `b_win = 0.5`), we can deduce that the estimated coefficient for window opening is statistically significantly different from 0.5 at the 0.05 level. We can test this more formally by using the `linearHypothesis()` function. Specifically,




